					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Another Guide for New Clerics</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:rob.the.blob@bigpond.com">Cuure of Erollisi Marr</a> | 
		            10/1/1999 6:49:49 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Greetings All,<BR>
<BR>
So you would be looking to join the Healing Profession. Allow me to guide you on the right path ...<BR>
<BR>
I started in a Little town called Freeport - it's on the coast, you would have heard of it.<BR>
<BR>
The very first thing you should do is go to the Cleric's Forum, and read the views and opinions of some players who already have Clerics as their characters - ignore the ones who whinge about things - I'll clear that up later ...<BR>
<BR>
Well, go on, I'll be here when you get back ... I swear by the  Lady Marr.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Oh, your back, well did you learn anything?  Good.  Well here we go ...<BR>
<BR>
1.   On Melee and being a Cleric<BR>
<BR>
You will find that you can Tank (melee monsters) around the West Gate of Freeport fairly easily, just don't forget to heal yourself between fights - hiding behind guards at the Gate to get your Mana / Hit Points back is accepted Wisdom - not cowardice :)<BR>
<BR>
There are a few Quests you can attempt (go to the Quests Forum for those).  NO, not now, later ... a little impatient, aren't you.<BR>
<BR>
Alright, so you get to level 3, and Large Bats, Rats and the occasional Decayed Skeleton are getting boring.<BR>
<BR>
Heed me now.  Find a Tank, Wizard or Monk, and make them your friend now.<BR>
<BR>
I suggest starting to group early, the earlier the better. You learn to trust the group, they learn to listen to you - you're the one who decides whether everyone should flee or stay (two words - Divine Aura).<BR>
<BR>
You will find that the earlier you learn to group the better you get at Strategy and EQ Tactics.  The advantage of Grouping???  You can take on tougher monsters (from Freeport, try the East Commonlands, watch for the GRIFFIN, always), get better XP and loot ... arghhhh, loot *sigh* ... the makings of Spells and Armour.<BR>
Later on, (when you are getting to level 7ish), you will have established a network of friends to call upon/look for when you feel like taking on some bigger monsters.<BR>
<BR>
Soloing is for Loners, and Clerics are not Loners, they are the Party Healers / Curers / Buffers ...<BR>
<BR>
2. On Healing and being a Cleric.<BR>
<BR>
Later on (about level 12+), you won't be able to Melee anything worth XP.  So what do you do now???   What the Cleric class was designed for.  You are not only the Healer of the party (both physical and spiritual).  You are the Strategist, the Tactician, the Organiser.<BR>
<BR>
Every party you work with will appreciate the following: <BR>
1) Those extra HP and AC that come from YOU <BR>
2) That extra resistance and curing of poisons and disease that come from YOU<BR>
3) That person who is always watching over the other players giving advice on when a Tank should Taunt to draw a mob onto them to releave another Tank is YOU<BR>
4) That person who has Divine Aura ready, tells the party to run and pulls the monster on themselves so the party can escape is YOU<BR>
In affect you are the BOSS.<BR>
<BR>
Now there are complaints about Clerics being forever poor ... there is that, we have to purchase Armour and Spells - as compared to Tanks - just Armour; or Wizards - just Spells.  Now before anyone mentions the Hybrid classes - Paladins, Rogues, etc who also wear Armour and cast Spells - they don't get Spells till level 9, so they already have their Armour and money for spells that we had to buy by then, and they are cheap for them (1gp at 9th level is not expensive, 1gp at 1st level is).<BR>
<BR>
There are a few different theories on Group playing a Cleric, basically, they are usually one of the following two:<BR>
<BR>
1) The Battle Healer - these are the Clerics who still melee with their group, but will pull out of combat to heal or cure (poison, disease, etc), then get back into combat - Dwarven Clerics tend to be of this Ilk (you can take the Combat out of a Dwarf, but you can't take the Dwarf out of Combat - hello my short friends).  This Cleric type is can be very handy for groups with a lower Tank to Wizard group, as the Cleric is giving a damage (not nearly as much as a Tank though) to shorten the life of the monster.<BR>
<BR>
2) The Strategist Healer - these are the Clerics who tend to stand back and watch their Group and make decisions from the rear.  Who needs the Heal, the Tank or the Wizard, what should I fix - the poisoned Monk or the 3 bubble Paladin.  This Cleric is the watcher and observer.  They can see where the party is weakening, if there are mobs on there way to aid there companion.  They can warn off a Tank to intercept the new mob, get the Wizard to nuke it, or tell the party GRIFFIN (this is done very often in the East Commonlands) or RUN.<BR>
<BR>
In either of the above you will come across Loot.  After a combat/melee/narrow escape, the first thing you will probably do is sit down and try to get your Mana back or Meditate if of high enough level (8+).  Now remember how I said even at level 3 you should Group and make friends. This is why. Your Group know that you need more money than anyone else, they appreciate you keeping them alive, they will share the loot with you.  If you let people get away with not sharing loot, not giving you items or not offering to pay for stuff for you, then you have the wisdom of a newt ... a dead newt. <BR>
<BR>
If no one shares Loot with you or gives you a choice of Armour or items found , leave them and find another group (if you Grouped early, you shouldn't have this problem)<BR>
<BR>
3.   Clerics are Boring???<BR>
Some people say Cleric get Boring - I can't think of anything more boring than standing there going, wow a new monster to bash, hit 'A' for autoattack, and then wait till Bash / Kick / smash become available.  You can play a Tank on autopilot, but it's the Cleric behind him that makes him a Great Autopilot.  <BR>
<BR>
As for playing a Wizard - I like armour  :)<BR>
<BR>
Well, I hope this gives you a few ideas on what/how/why to play a Cleric.<BR>
<BR>
... and remember, have fun out there.  Heal / Cure / Buff anyone and everyone, and people will be singing your praises.  Rewards will come your way.<BR>
<BR>
Cuure of Erollisi Marr<BR>
Healer of the Lady's People
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
